      <p>
        Key points which must be kept in mind during the interview:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>Interviewers respect how you reach the solution rather than how quickly you answer. If you know the answer,
          they move on to the next question. They keep asking questions until you take enough time to think over a
          problem and conclude. They want to check your thought process.
        </li>
        <li>If possible, it is beneficial to give an interview at the beginning of the slot. Interviewers are relaxed at
          the start of the interview, keep enjoying and asking good questions but get tired and disinterested by the end
          of the slot.
        </li>
        <li>
          In the interview preparation, theoretical and technical preparation are the aspects that everybody knows but
          how to give an interview is a completely different game. This creates a huge difference. Generally, students
          don’t focus on this skill, which is very important.

        </li>
        <li>
          Interviewers check your communication skills, problem-solving approach, and how you accept the challenges
          throughout the interview. If you don’t know the answers, take 2 or 3 minutes, think about the problems, and
          stay on the right track but don’t give an answer you cannot defend. They also check how accountable you are
          for your work.

        </li>
        <li>
          It happens in the interview that you learn new things about yourself. Your introduction grows in each
          interview successively. You think everyone has given such a basic introduction, what unique things to be
          added, and you tried to add bits and pieces. You need not prepare everything you will say during the
          interview. But make sure you are prepared to be able to think clearly and say what you need to during the
          interview.

        </li>
        <li>
          Give a simple and original answer to which you are closely connected and understandable to the interviewers.
          You don;t need to give scripted detailed solutions. It can sometimes create problems during the interview,
          because either the interviewer knows your source and finds out it is scripted or they are not able to
          understand what you are saying. Always maintain your originality towards answering the questions and develop
          your methodology rather than end products.

        </li>
        <li>
          The placement drive takes a heavy toll on your mental health. Every test, every shortlist, every interview, it
          just keeps on mounting the pressure on you so it is very important to keep yourself grounded, level-headed and
          focussed throughout the process. If you make sure that happens, you will be rewarded.

        </li>
        <li>
          If possible, try to end your interview on a slightly lighter note, at the end of the day interviewers are
          human as well, and appealing to their human side cannot hurt your chances.

        </li>
        <li>
          At the end of the day, if you are like me, you will be playing the percentage game. Do whatever you think
          improves your chances of getting where you want, and if there’s something else that does the same in less time
          and effort, do that first.
        </li>
      </ol>
